            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this construction loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to mirror how real-world construction
                loans work: you draw funds in stages, pay interest-only on the
                outstanding balance, and then either pay off or roll the balance
                into a permanent mortgage.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Construction phase: interest-only draws</h3>
              <p>During construction, most lenders structure the loan as:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Multiple draws</strong> as work is completed
                  (foundation, framing, rough-in, finishes, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest-only payments</strong> on the amount drawn so
                  far.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal due at completion</strong> or converted into
                  a standard mortgage.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator models this by building a month-by-month schedule
                of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Draws funded in each month.</li>
                <li>Outstanding balance after each draw.</li>
                <li>Interest-only payment based on the current balance.</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Monthly interest formula</p>
                <p>
                  If \(B_t\) is the outstanding balance during month \(t\), and
                  the annual interest rate is \(r\), then the monthly interest
                  payment is:
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{Interest}_t = B_t \times \frac{r}{12} \]</p>
                <p>
                  For weekly or bi-weekly payments, the calculator converts the
                  annual rate to an equivalent periodic rate based on 52 or 26
                  payments per year.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Draw schedules: simple vs advanced</h3>
              <p>You can choose between two draw schedule modes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple (even draws)</strong> – You specify the number
                  of draws. The calculator assumes equal amounts spaced evenly
                  over the construction period.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Advanced (custom draws)</strong> – You enter each draw
                  amount and the month it occurs. This is useful if you have a
                  builder’s draw schedule or lender term sheet.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The sum of all draws is capped at the construction loan amount.
                If your custom draws exceed the loan limit, the calculator will
                show a warning.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Permanent mortgage after construction</h3>
              <p>
                Many construction loans are structured as
                <strong>construction-to-permanent</strong> (one-time close)
                loans. After the home is complete:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The outstanding construction balance becomes the mortgage
                  principal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The loan converts to a standard amortizing mortgage (fixed
                  rate and term).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Mortgage payment formula</p>
                <p>
                  If \(P\) is the principal, \(i\) is the monthly interest rate,
                  and \(n\) is the number of monthly payments:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Payment} = P \times \frac{i(1+i)^n}{(1+i)^n - 1} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Cash required and equity</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator compares your
                <strong>total project cost</strong> to the
                <strong>loan funds used</strong> to estimate your required cash
                contribution:
              </p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{Equity (cash required)} = \text{Total project cost} -
                \text{Loan funds used} \]
              </p>
              <p>
                This is a simplified view and does not include closing costs,
                interest reserves, contingency, or lender fees, which can be
                significant.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for planning a construction loan</h2>
              <h3>Verify your builder’s draw schedule</h3>
              <p>
                Ask your builder for a detailed draw schedule and plug it into
                the Advanced mode. This helps you see how your interest-only
                payments will ramp up as more of the loan is drawn.
              </p>

              <h3>Plan for delays and cost overruns</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Increase the construction period to see the impact of delays
                  on total interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Test higher project costs to understand how much extra equity
                  you may need.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider adding a contingency (e.g., 5–10%) to your project
                  cost input.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Talk to lenders early</h3>
              <p>Different lenders have different rules for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Maximum loan-to-cost (LTC) and loan-to-value (LTV) ratios.
                </li>
                <li>Interest-only period length and extension options.</li>
                <li>
                  Whether the loan automatically converts to a permanent
                  mortgage.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this calculator to get a realistic picture of payments and
                cash needs, then confirm details with a qualified lender or
                mortgage professional.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Construction loan calculator FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >How is interest calculated on a construction loan?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Most construction loans are interest-only during the build.
                    Each period (usually monthly), the lender multiplies your
                    current outstanding balance by the periodic interest rate.
                    If your annual rate is 8%, the approximate monthly rate is
                    8% ÷ 12 ≈ 0.667%. If your balance that month is $250,000,
                    your interest payment is about $1,667. As more draws are
                    taken, the balance and interest payment increase.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >What is the difference between a construction-only and
                      construction-to-permanent loan?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    A construction-only loan finances just the build. When
                    construction is complete, you must refinance into a separate
                    permanent mortgage, which means a second closing and
                    potentially new fees. A construction-to-permanent loan
                    (one-time close) combines both phases: you close once, pay
                    interest-only during construction, and then the loan
                    automatically converts to a standard mortgage at completion.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Why do my interest-only payments change over time?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Because you only pay interest on the amount that has been
                    drawn. Early in the project, your outstanding balance is
                    low, so interest payments are smaller. As more draws are
                    taken, the balance grows and so do the interest-only
                    payments. The calculator’s timeline table shows how this
                    typically ramps up month by month.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Does this calculator include closing costs and
                      fees?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    No. This calculator focuses on principal and interest for
                    the construction loan and optional permanent mortgage. It
                    does not include lender fees, appraisal, inspections, title,
                    or other closing costs. For a more complete budget, add an
                    estimate of those costs to your total project cost and
                    discuss details with your lender or closing agent.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Is this construction loan calculator suitable for
                      owner-builders?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Yes. Whether you are using a general contractor or acting as
                    an owner-builder, the math behind the loan is the same:
                    staged draws, interest-only payments, and a final payoff or
                    conversion. However, some lenders have stricter requirements
                    or higher down payments for owner-builders, so always
                    confirm terms with your lender.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
